<p>Lakawon Island is the 13-hectare sandbar shaped like a banana, sitting roughly 3 kilometers off the Cadiz City coast in northern Negros Occidental. The local tourism office calls it the quiet alternative to Boracay, which is half marketing and half true. The beach is long and pale, the swimming area is shallow, and the off-shore TawHai floating bar is the headline activity people drive up from Bacolod to try.</p>
<p>This is not a flashy resort island, and that is the point. The accommodations are simple nipa huts and canopy tents, the food is grilled seafood, and the evenings end early because there is no nightlife beyond the floating bar. Tara, here is the slow weekend plan if you have two nights to spare.</p>
<h2>Getting to Lakawon</h2>
<p>The starting point is Bacolod City. From the new Bacolod Silay airport, take a van or grab to the Northbound Ceres Terminal in Bacolod. From there, board a Ceres Liner bus heading to Cadiz or San Carlos and get off at the Cadiz Public Market, which is around 65 to 70 kilometers north of Bacolod. The ride is around two hours on the highway.</p>
<h3>The Cadiz Boat</h3>
<p>From the public market, ride a tricycle to the Cadiz Boat Terminal at Barangay Cadiz Viejo. The boat to Lakawon runs on a fixed schedule, usually from 7 a.m. to 4 p.m., and the crossing takes around 20 minutes on a calm day. Check with the boatmen or your resort for the latest schedule because trips get suspended when the wind picks up.</p>
<h2>Day One: Settle and Float</h2>
<p>Drop your bags, change into beach clothes, and walk the long stretch of sand on the bay-facing side. The water is calm and shallow for a long way out, which makes it good for kids and casual swimmers. Lunch is a grilled fish and rice plate from the kitchen, which is the standard option on the island.</p>
<h3>TawHai Floating Bar</h3>
<p>The TawHai floating bar is the activity most weekenders come for. The bar is a wooden platform anchored off the beach, with a thatched roof and basic seating, and a small kitchen for snacks and drinks. The crossing to the platform is by short banca shuttle, and you pay an entry fee at the beach office. The vibe is calm in the afternoon, livelier in the late afternoon when the day-trippers arrive.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Snorkel and Kayak</h2>
<p>Spend the morning either snorkeling off the reef edge near the floating bar, or paddling a rented kayak along the calm bay side. The reef is not the most colorful in the country, but the marine life is steady and the water clarity is sulit during the dry months. Lunch is another grilled fish plate, then a long nap under the palm shade, then sunset on the western tip of the island.</p>
<h3>What to Bring</h3>
<ul>
<li>Cash for the boat fees, the entrance fees, and the food, the island has limited card service</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen for the snorkel session</li>
<li>A power bank, the power is generator-based and on a schedule</li>
<li>A light rashguard for the boat shuttle to the floating bar</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the early evenings</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone</li>
</ul>
<h2>Best Time to Go</h2>
<p>The dry season from November to May is the steady window. The seas are calm, the boat schedules are reliable, and the late afternoons are easy. Holy Week and Christmas week fill up fast, so book the hut or tent at least a few weeks ahead. The rainy months from June to October are doable but the boat crossings get cancelled more often.</p>
<h2>Getting Back to Bacolod</h2>
<p>The afternoon boat back to Cadiz Viejo leaves around 4 p.m. From the boat terminal, the same tricycle and Ceres Liner combination takes you back to Bacolod in around two and a half hours. If you have time before your flight, stop at Manokan Country in Bacolod for the proper inasal lunch before heading to the airport.</p>
<p>For places to stay in Bacolod before or after the island, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298444-Bacolod_Negros_Occidental_Province_Negros_Island_Region_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Bacolod has the better airport access and the better food scene.</p>
<h2>Why Lakawon Still Works</h2>
<p>Lakawon is the version of a Visayas island weekend that has not been over-developed. The beach is long, the floating bar is a fun novelty, and the slow pace is the actual product. If your itinerary already covers Bacolod for the Masskara Festival or the heritage day in Silay, Lakawon is the natural add-on weekend.</p>
