        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tayabas City is the heritage stop most Quezon travelers skip on the way to Lucban for the Pahiyas Festival. The town sits at the foot of Mount Banahaw, around three hours south of Manila, and the historic core is small enough to walk in one slow day. The two anchors are the Basilica of Saint Michael the Archangel, the largest Catholic church in Quezon province, and the Malagonlong Bridge, a 445-foot arched stone span from 1840 that still carries foot traffic over the Dumacaa River.</p>
<p>This is not a postcard day. It is a walking day with old stone, sweet kakanin, and the kwento of a town that has been a colonial municipal capital since 1734.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, the easiest route is a Lucena-bound bus from Cubao or Buendia, around three to four hours on a clear day. Operators like <a href="https://www.jacliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">JAC Liner</a> and JAM run the route at high frequency. Get off at the Lucena Grand Terminal, then take a jeepney bound for Tayabas, which is around a 20-minute ride and lets you off at the town plaza.</p>
<h3>If You Have a Car</h3>
<p>The drive from Manila uses SLEX and the STAR Tollway, then continues on the Maharlika Highway south. Total drive time is around three hours without traffic, and parking is easy around the church plaza.</p>
<h2>Morning: The Basilica</h2>
<p>The Basilica of Saint Michael the Archangel is the natural starting point. The current stone structure dates from 1856, although the parish itself was founded in 1580. The church is shaped like a key, which is why locals call it Susi ng Tayabas, the key of Tayabas. The interior has a baroque retablo and stations of the cross painted in the Filipino folk style. Mass schedules are posted at the entrance.</p>
<h3>Plaza and Walking Core</h3>
<p>The plaza in front of the basilica is the start of the heritage walking loop. The streets around it are lined with ancestral houses in mixed Spanish-American style, some preserved, some falling apart, some converted to small carinderias and souvenir stalls.</p>
<h2>Late Morning: Budin and Yema Cake</h2>
<p>Tayabas has two pasalubong items worth carrying home. The first is the budin, a soft cassava cake baked in banana leaves and sold along Kalye Budin near the plaza. The shelf life is two to three days unrefrigerated and the texture stays moist. The second is the Rodilla yema cake, a chiffon log layered with rich yema custard, slightly salted, and now sold across the country but still best where it started.</p>
<h3>Lunch Recommendation</h3>
<p>For lunch, the carinderias near the church serve standard Quezon plates: pancit habhab, tinapayang manok, and pinangat. The hot bowl of bulalo at the small canteens is also a reliable choice on a cool Tayabas afternoon.</p>
<h2>Afternoon: Malagonlong Bridge</h2>
<p>The Malagonlong Bridge is around four kilometers out of the town center, easily reached by tricycle. The bridge is a five-arch stone span over the Dumacaa River, built in 1840 during the Spanish colonial period using brick and limestone. It is now a National Cultural Treasure and one of the oldest stone bridges in the Philippines. Walk across it slowly, the deck is wide enough for foot traffic only, and the view of the river below is calm.</p>
<h3>Hot Spring Wading Pool</h3>
<p>If you have time before the bus home, drop by the small Tayabas hot spring complex on the way back to the highway. The pools are roofed and modest, fed by a natural warm source, and the wading is good for sore feet after a day of walking. Bring slippers and a small towel.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Comfortable walking shoes, the heritage loop is on uneven cobble in places</li>
<li>A hat or cap, the basilica plaza has minimal shade at noon</li>
<li>Cash, the small kakanin and carinderia stops are cash-only</li>
<li>A small notebook if you like to log the inscriptions at the bridge and the church</li>
<li>A reusable water bottle, refills at the carinderias</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Sleep If You Stay Over</h2>
<p>Tayabas does not have a deep hotel inventory, so most overnight travelers base in Lucena City, around 20 minutes away by jeepney. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g1808476-Lucena_Quezon_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Lucena has the better dinner spots and the easier morning bus back to Manila.</p>
<p>Tayabas is the slow heritage day that pairs well with a longer Quezon weekend. Pair it with Lucban for Pahiyas or with Sariaya for more ancestral houses, and you have a complete three-day plan with three different walking towns.</p>
