        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Kamay ni Hesus is the religious complex on a hill in Lucban, Quezon, founded by Father Joey Faller in the early 2000s. The headline structure is a 50-foot statue of the Risen Christ at the top of a 305-step climb, with life-size Stations of the Cross dioramas spread along the way up. On Holy Week and on Sundays during festival season, the place is busy with pilgrims. The rest of the year, it is a quiet hillside climb with a long view of the Quezon countryside at the top.</p>
<p>This is the half-day read for the off-peak visit, paired with a slow Lucban lunch and a stop at the basilica in town.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a Lucena-bound bus on <a href="https://www.jacliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">JAC Liner</a> or JAM Liner from Cubao or Buendia. The ride is around three to four hours. Get off at the Lucena Grand Terminal, then take a jeepney bound for Lucban, around 45 minutes through the Banahaw foothills. The Kamay ni Hesus complex is a short tricycle ride from the Lucban town center.</p>
<h3>If You Have a Car</h3>
<p>From Manila, SLEX to STAR Tollway, then Maharlika Highway south, then the turnoff to Lucban. Drive time is around three hours and parking is available at the foot of the hill.</p>
<h2>The Climb</h2>
<p>The full climb has 305 concrete steps, divided into shaded landings with the life-size Stations of the Cross dioramas. The path is not steep, but it is steady, and the older pilgrims pace themselves. Take the climb slowly, pause at the dioramas, and bring water.</p>
<h3>Stations of the Cross</h3>
<p>The 14 stations are sculpted in concrete, painted in muted tones, and placed in small chapels or open-air alcoves at each landing. The climb is meant to be reflective. If you came for the photo at the top, the calm read is still to stop at each station for at least a minute.</p>
<h3>The Risen Christ Statue</h3>
<p>The summit holds the 50-foot statue of the Risen Christ, surrounded by a small viewing deck. The view from the top covers the Lucban rooftops, the surrounding rice fields, and on clear mornings, Mount Banahaw to the south. There is a small chapel near the statue for prayer and a few benches for sitting out the afternoon.</p>
<h2>Down the Hill</h2>
<p>The descent has a separate Garden of Eden path with biblical-themed sculptures, including the giant Noah's Ark structure and the Ten Commandments tablets. The walk down is shorter and easier than the climb up. At the foot of the hill, the souvenir stalls sell rosaries, religious medals, and small bottles of holy water.</p>
<h2>Lunch in Lucban</h2>
<p>The town of Lucban is a 10-minute tricycle ride from the shrine. Two dishes anchor any Lucban food stop. The first is pancit habhab, the fine miki noodles tossed in soy and chicken broth and traditionally served on a banana leaf eaten without utensils. The second is longganisa Lucban, the garlicky pork sausage that pairs with garlic rice and a sunny-side egg. Buddy's and the small carinderias around the town plaza serve both.</p>
<h3>Basilica of Saint Louis of Toulouse</h3>
<p>After lunch, walk over to the Basilica of Saint Louis of Toulouse, the parish church on the Lucban town plaza. The current stone structure dates from the 18th century and has the muted folk-baroque interior typical of southern Tagalog churches. It is also the spiritual center of the Pahiyas Festival held every May 15.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Comfortable shoes with grip, the steps get slick in the rain</li>
<li>A hat or cap and reusable water bottle for the climb</li>
<li>Small bills for the donation boxes and souvenir stalls</li>
<li>A light umbrella for the late afternoon walk down</li>
<li>Modest clothing if you plan to attend mass at the basilica</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The off-peak window is the best for the calm climb. Avoid Holy Week, the days around Christmas, and the May 15 Pahiyas Festival itself if you want the quiet version. Early morning visits, before 9 a.m., catch the cool air and the soft light at the top.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>If you are pairing the shrine with the Pahiyas Festival, book a stay in Lucban months ahead because the small inventory fills up fast. Outside festival weekends, Lucena City is the easier base. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g1808476-Lucena_Quezon_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Kamay ni Hesus is the kind of stop that rewards the slow visit. Climb at your own pace, sit at the top for a while, then go down for the pancit habhab. The day will feel longer than the three or four hours it actually took.</p>
