        'excerpt' => 'The Cebu to Bohol crossing takes around two hours by fast craft. Here is the operator read, the port differences, and how to book without paying terminal markup.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Cebu to Bohol crossing is one of the busiest inter-island ferry routes in the Visayas and the easiest way to combine the two islands in one trip. The fast-craft ride from Cebu City Pier to Tagbilaran takes around two hours on a calm day, and the operators that run the route most reliably are OceanJet, SuperCat, and FastCat. This is the practical first-timer read on which to pick, how to book, and what to expect at the ports.</p>
<h2>The Three Main Operators</h2>
<h3>OceanJet</h3>
<p>OceanJet is the highest-frequency operator on the route, with multiple daily trips between Cebu City and Tagbilaran. The boats offer three seat classes: Open Air on the back deck, Tourist Class in the main cabin, and Business Class with the better seats and aircon. Book at <a href="https://oceanjet.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">OceanJet</a> in advance because peak-season slots sell out.</p>
<h3>SuperCat</h3>
<p>SuperCat operates under Chelsea Logistics and runs the same Cebu City to Tagbilaran route with a similar class structure: Economy, Tourist, and Business. The schedule is less frequent than OceanJet but still reliable for the major daily slots.</p>
<h3>FastCat</h3>
<p>FastCat is the RORO option for travelers bringing a car or motorbike. The boats are slower than the fast craft and they dock at Tubigon Port on the western Bohol side, not Tagbilaran. From Tubigon, you drive or ride to Tagbilaran City in around one to one and a half hours. FastCat is the cheaper option for foot passengers too, but the longer crossing means most tourists pick the fast craft.</p>
<h2>The Two Bohol Ports</h2>
<p>OceanJet and SuperCat land at Tagbilaran Port, which is right in Tagbilaran City and close to the airport. From the pier, you can take a tricycle, taxi, or pre-arranged van to Panglao, Loboc, or the countryside tour starting points.</p>
<p>FastCat lands at Tubigon Port, on the northwestern Bohol coast. From Tubigon, the V-hire vans to Tagbilaran run from morning to early evening and the ride is around one and a half hours through the inland highway. The Tubigon route is the better starting point if you are heading straight to Anda or the northern Bohol coast.</p>
<h2>Booking the Ticket</h2>
<p>Book online a few days ahead during peak season, which runs from December to May and on Holy Week. The walk-up counters at the Cebu Port still sell tickets, but the cheap classes go first and you may end up paying for the Business Class slot.</p>
<h3>The Online Booking Steps</h3>
<ol>
<li>Pick the operator and the date</li>
<li>Pick the time slot, the morning trips are calmer water</li>
<li>Pick the seat class, Tourist is the standard middle option</li>
<li>Pay with credit card or e-wallet</li>
<li>Save the confirmation, you will need it at the terminal</li>
</ol>
<p>You can also book through Klook or 12go, which aggregate the schedules. The terminal fee at the Cebu Port is paid separately at the gate and is cash-only.</p>
<h2>At the Cebu Port</h2>
<p>Arrive at least one hour before departure. The Cebu City Pier has multiple terminals, so confirm which terminal your operator uses. Bring a printed or screenshot copy of your booking. The boarding process includes a baggage scan, a terminal fee payment, and a seat assignment if you booked Tourist or Business.</p>
<h3>What to Bring On Board</h3>
<ul>
<li>A light jacket or shawl, the cabin aircon runs cold</li>
<li>A reusable water bottle, the on-board refreshment is paid</li>
<li>Earphones, the boats play in-cabin movies on loop</li>
<li>Motion sickness meds if you are sensitive, the open seas can swell</li>
<li>A power bank, charging ports on board are limited</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Return Trip</h2>
<p>Book the return ticket the day you arrive in Bohol if you have not already, especially if your departure date falls on a weekend or holiday. The afternoon Tagbilaran to Cebu trips sell out faster than the morning slots.</p>
<h2>The One Tip Most First-Timers Skip</h2>
<p>If you are prone to seasickness, book the morning trip. The seas between Cebu and Bohol are calmer before noon, and the afternoon swells can make the open-air seats uncomfortable. The Tourist Class enclosed seats are the safest pick for a smooth crossing.</p>
<p>The Cebu to Bohol ferry route is one of the few inter-island crossings in the Philippines that is actually easy to plan. Pick OceanJet for frequency, SuperCat for the alternative schedule, FastCat if you need the RORO, and book the seat class that matches the weather and the crowd.</p>
