        'source_url' => 'https://outoftownblog.com/diving-apo-island/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Out of Town Blog',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Apo Island Diving Day from Dauin: Marine Sanctuary Read',
        'slug' => 'apo-island-diving-day-dauin-marine-sanctuary',
        'excerpt' => 'Apo Island is the community-managed marine sanctuary off Dauin. Here is the diving day plan, the two main sites, and what to expect from a steady drift.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Apo Island sits around 25 kilometers off the southern Negros coast, easily reached from Dauin or Malatapay by banca. The island has been a community-managed marine sanctuary since 1982, one of the earliest in the country, and the reef has recovered to the point where the turtle population is now what most day-trip divers come for. This is the practical read on the dive day, the two main sites, and the surface intervals worth planning for.</p>
<h2>The Two Main Dive Sites</h2>
<h3>Coconut Point</h3>
<p>Coconut Point is the headline drift dive on the northeast side of the island. The current can pick up sharp, especially around the lunar tides, which is why the dive operators brief carefully before you giant-stride off the banca. The reward is a steady drift along a wall covered in soft coral and sea fans, with schools of jacks and the occasional tuna or trevally passing through. Depth ranges from 12 to 30 meters depending on the route the divemaster picks.</p>
<h3>Chapel Point</h3>
<p>Chapel Point on the western side is the calmer alternative. The drift is gentle, the wall slopes more gradually, and the turtle sightings are reliable. This is the better site for first-time Apo divers and for the second dive of the day after Coconut Point. Macro photographers tend to favor Chapel for the easier hover time.</p>
<h2>The Day Plan</h2>
<p>Most operators in Dauin run the Apo Island day trip as a two-tank dive with surface interval on the island beach. The schedule usually looks like this:</p>
<ol>
<li>Hotel pickup at 7:30 a.m.</li>
<li>Banca departure from Malatapay or Dauin pier at 8 a.m.</li>
<li>First dive at Coconut Point or Mamsa Point around 9:30 a.m.</li>
<li>Surface interval at the island beach with a packed lunch</li>
<li>Second dive at Chapel Point or Rock Point around noon</li>
<li>Return to Dauin by 2 p.m.</li>
</ol>
<p>The surface interval on the beach is part of the experience. Walk the small village path, watch the resident turtles surface near the shore for the snorkelers, and refill on water before the second dive.</p>
<h2>What to Expect on the Drift</h2>
<p>Apo Island sits in the Bohol Sea on the path of the Equatorial Current, which is why the drift can be strong. The divemasters are experienced and the briefing is honest. If you are an Open Water diver with fewer than 20 logged dives, ask for the calmer site for your first Apo dive. If you are AOW or higher, the standard rotation works.</p>
<h3>The Turtle Sightings</h3>
<p>Green turtles and hawksbills are common, and the resident population has gotten used to divers. Keep your distance, do not touch, and let the turtles approach if they want to. The sanctuary rules are strict and the divemasters enforce them.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Your dive certification card and logbook</li>
<li>A 3mm wetsuit is usually enough, the water is around 27 to 29 degrees Celsius</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen for the beach surface interval</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet on the banca</li>
<li>Cash for the marine sanctuary fee, paid at the Apo Island ranger station</li>
<li>A hat and a reusable water bottle</li>
<li>Motion sickness meds if you are sensitive, the crossing can swell</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Marine Sanctuary Fee</h2>
<p>The fee is collected at the ranger station when the banca lands and is separate from the dive operator's package. The fee covers the sanctuary management, the community ranger salaries, and the day-to-day enforcement of the no-touch and no-fishing zones. Bring small bills.</p>
<h2>Getting to Dauin</h2>
<p>From Manila or Cebu, fly into Dumaguete on <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or Philippine Airlines. From Dumaguete, the easiest way to Dauin is a tricycle or a hotel-arranged van, around 30 minutes south on the coastal road. Most dive resorts include the transfer in the package.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Dauin is the obvious base because it is the closest dive town to Apo Island and to the black sand macro diving along the coast. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664681-Dauin_Negros_Oriental_Province_Negros_Island_Region_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Most properties have an in-house dive shop.</p>
<h2>Best Season to Dive</h2>
<p>The best diving window is from March to June, when the visibility is at its peak and the surface conditions are calm. October to February is also workable, but the wind picks up and the banca crossing can be bumpy.</p>
<p>Apo Island is one of the longest-running marine sanctuary success stories in the country. Plan the two-tank day, respect the sanctuary rules, and the drift will reward you.</p>
