        'source_url' => 'https://outoftownblog.com/coco-grove-beach-resort-siquijor/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Out of Town Blog',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Coco Grove Base for a Slow Siquijor Weekend: San Juan Coastline Read',
        'slug' => 'coco-grove-san-juan-siquijor-slow-weekend-base',
        'excerpt' => 'San Juan is the calm coastline on Siquijor with the best swimmable beach. Here is why basing in the Coco Grove area gives you a smooth weekend.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The San Juan side of Siquijor is the long stretch of pale beach on the western coast, anchored by the Coco Grove area and Tubod Marine Sanctuary. The water is shallow, the sand is fine, and the swimming is good at any tide. This is the practical read on why basing your slow Siquijor weekend in this area gives you the smoothest combination of beach mornings, scooter loops, and quiet evenings.</p>
<h2>Why San Juan, Not Siquijor Town</h2>
<p>Siquijor town on the eastern coast is the main port and the more practical arrival point. But the swimming and the beach scene cluster on the western and southern coasts, with San Juan being the most developed of the calm sections. The shopping and the cafe scene are along the San Juan main road, the boat trips to Apo and the smaller dive sites start from the same coastline, and the sunsets are the best on this side of the island.</p>
<h3>The Coco Grove Area</h3>
<p>The Coco Grove area refers to a stretch of coast just south of San Juan town proper, named after the long-running Coco Grove Beach Resort that anchors the area. The cluster of resorts and small inns along this stretch share the same calm beach and the same Tubod Marine Sanctuary access. If you stay anywhere in this strip, the beach mornings work the same way.</p>
<h2>Day One: Arrive and Swim</h2>
<p>Arrive in Siquijor by morning fast craft from Dumaguete, around an hour by OceanJet. From Siquijor Port, take a tricycle or a hotel transfer to San Juan, around 30 minutes on the coastal road. Drop your bags, change, and walk straight to the beach.</p>
<h3>Tubod Marine Sanctuary</h3>
<p>The Tubod Marine Sanctuary is a 6-hectare no-take zone right off the Coco Grove coast. Snorkel rentals are available from the small huts along the beach. The reef starts in shallow water and slopes down to around 8 meters, with a healthy coral cover and steady reef fish populations. The afternoon swim is the easy first activity.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Island Loop</h2>
<p>Rent a scooter from the front desk or any of the rental shops along the San Juan main road. The Siquijor coastal road forms a 72-kilometer loop around the whole island, doable in one slow day with the right stops.</p>
<h3>The Standard Loop Stops</h3>
<ul>
<li>Salagdoong Beach on the eastern side for the cliff jump platforms</li>
<li>Cambugahay Falls in Lazi for the rope swing and natural pools</li>
<li>The Lazi Convent, one of the oldest in the country, for the heritage stop</li>
<li>The old Balete tree in Lazi with the fish spa pool at the roots</li>
<li>Cantabon Cave for a short guided spelunking visit</li>
<li>Capilay Spring Park in San Juan town for the sunset wading</li>
</ul>
<h3>Lunch Stop</h3>
<p>Stop for lunch at Lazi or at Maria town along the southeastern coast. The small carinderias serve standard Visayan plates: sinigang, grilled fish, kinilaw, and rice. Eat slowly, the loop is not a race.</p>
<h2>Day Three: Slow Morning, Late Departure</h2>
<p>The third morning is the calm one. Have breakfast on the beach, walk the sand at low tide, and read on the lounger until lunch. The OceanJet fast craft back to Dumaguete runs in the afternoon, so you have time for one more swim and a late checkout.</p>
<h3>Folk Healers</h3>
<p>If you want to add a cultural stop, the folk healing tradition is still active in San Antonio, Siquijor, especially around Holy Week. The healers practice a syncretic blend of Catholic and indigenous rituals, and the cooperative welcomes respectful visitors year-round. Bring a small donation and approach with the same courtesy you would at any sacred space.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen for the Tubod snorkel</li>
<li>A scooter helmet for the island loop, or use the one from the rental</li>
<li>Cash in small bills for the loop entrance fees, the cave guide, and the food</li>
<li>A dry bag for the boat hops and the falls swims</li>
<li>A light rashguard for the long swims</li>
<li>A power bank, the brownouts in Siquijor are still occasional</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Siquijor</h2>
<p>From Dumaguete, OceanJet runs multiple daily fast-craft trips, around one hour. Book in advance at <a href="https://oceanjet.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">OceanJet</a>. The other route is from Tagbilaran, Bohol, with less frequent crossings. Most travelers arrive via Dumaguete because the flight inventory into Dumaguete is deeper than into Siquijor.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The San Juan and Coco Grove area has a mix of resorts, mid-range inns, and small guesthouses, mostly within walking distance of the beach. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729450-Siquijor_Island_Siquijor_Province_Negros_Island_Region_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>San Juan is the version of Siquijor that earns the trip without needing a tour bus. Base on this side, ride the loop on day two, and let the calm beach mornings do the rest.</p>
