        'source_url' => 'https://outoftownblog.com/philippine-hot-air-balloon-festival-2024/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Out of Town Blog',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Philippine Hot Air Balloon Festival at New Clark City: Weekend Plan',
        'slug' => 'philippine-hot-air-balloon-festival-clark-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'The balloon festival moved to New Clark City in Capas. Here is the weekend plan, the predawn arrival time, and what to wear when the field is cold.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Philippine Hot Air Balloon Festival is one of the oldest aviation festivals in the country, dating back to 1994. The event was originally held at the Clark Field in Pampanga and has since moved to the larger New Clark City grounds in Capas, Tarlac. The festival runs across three days, usually in late January or early February, and the headline activity is the predawn balloon inflation that fills the field with color before sunrise.</p>
<p>This is the practical weekend plan for first-time festival-goers, with the predawn arrival logic, the parking notes, and what to wear when the open field is cold.</p>
<h2>The Predawn Arrival</h2>
<p>The balloons inflate before sunrise, when the wind is calm enough for safe lift-off. The schedule means you need to be at the field by 4:30 a.m. to catch the inflation from the start, with the actual mass ascension usually beginning around 6 a.m. Arriving at 7 a.m. is too late, the balloons are already gone.</p>
<h3>The Drive Out</h3>
<p>From Manila, leave by 2:30 a.m. to clear the NLEX and SCTEX without any holiday traffic. The drive is around two and a half hours. From Clark, the drive to New Clark City is around 45 minutes on the Subic-Clark stretch.</p>
<h3>Parking</h3>
<p>The festival uses designated parking zones inside the New Clark City complex, with shuttle rides from the parking to the spectator field. The shuttle line gets long after 5 a.m., so the earlier you arrive, the shorter the wait. Bring small bills for the parking fee.</p>
<h2>What Happens Across the Three Days</h2>
<h3>Day One: Opening</h3>
<p>The Friday opening usually includes the official launch, a smaller balloon ascension, and the start of the aviation static displays. The crowd is the lightest, which makes Friday the calm option if you have flexibility.</p>
<h3>Day Two: Main Day</h3>
<p>The Saturday is the headline day, with the full balloon mass ascension at sunrise, the skydiving demonstrations during the day, the aerobatic flying displays, and the kite-flying competition in the afternoon. The crowd is at its biggest, so plan the arrival time accordingly.</p>
<h3>Day Three: Closing</h3>
<p>The Sunday repeats the morning mass ascension, with the closing ceremony in the afternoon. If you can only pick one day, Saturday is the most complete experience, but Friday is the easiest in terms of crowds.</p>
<h2>What to Wear</h2>
<p>The open field at New Clark City gets cold in the predawn hours, especially in January. Layer up properly.</p>
<ul>
<li>A fleece or light jacket for the predawn cold</li>
<li>A scarf or buff for the wind on the field</li>
<li>Closed shoes, the field is grass and uneven in places</li>
<li>A cap for the late morning sun</li>
<li>Sunblock for the daytime aerial displays</li>
<li>A reusable water bottle, refills at the festival kiosks</li>
</ul>
<h2>Food and Vendors</h2>
<p>The festival has a food village with rows of stalls selling Filipino street food, grilled meats, kakanin, and a few coffee carts. The lines get long around 7 a.m. once the morning ascension finishes, so eat breakfast either before you leave Manila or in the early predawn hours before the inflation starts.</p>
<h3>Bring</h3>
<ul>
<li>Breakfast snacks: hard-boiled eggs, pandesal, fruit</li>
<li>A thermos of hot coffee for the predawn wait</li>
<li>Trash bags, the festival is leave-no-trace in principle</li>
<li>A foldable picnic mat for sitting on the grass</li>
</ul>
<h2>Photography Notes</h2>
<p>The best photos are the balloons against the sunrise color in the eastern sky. A camera with manual settings works better than the phone for the low-light inflation, but the phones do fine once the sun comes up. Bring a small tripod if you want the long-exposure shots of the burner glow.</p>
<h2>The Other Activities</h2>
<p>If you stay through the day, the static displays of vintage aircraft, the parachute demonstration jumps, and the radio-controlled model aircraft show all run on rolling schedules. The kite-flying competition in the afternoon is a calm activity to wind down with after the morning rush.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>The two practical bases are Clark and Angeles City, both around 45 minutes from New Clark City. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303701-Angeles_City_Pampanga_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Book at least a month ahead because the festival weekend fills up the local inventory.</p>
<h2>Pairing the Weekend</h2>
<p>If you have a full weekend, pair the festival with a Saturday afternoon Kapampangan food tour in Angeles, a Sunday morning visit to the Aerospace Museum at Clark, and a stop at one of the Bamban or Capas heritage sites on the way home. Two days of aviation, food, and Central Luzon history.</p>
<p>The hot air balloon festival is the rare large-scale Philippine event that still feels well-run because the New Clark City venue has the space. Plan the predawn arrival, layer up for the field, and let the balloons do the rest.</p>
