        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Minalungao National Park in Nueva Ecija: River Bamboo Raft Day Trip',
        'slug' => 'minalungao-national-park-nueva-ecija-day-trip',
        'excerpt' => 'Minalungao is the 2,000-hectare park in Gen Tinio with limestone walls and a jade-green river. Here is the day plan, the bamboo raft, and how to get there.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Minalungao National Park sits in General Tinio, Nueva Ecija, on the eastern edge of the Sierra Madre foothills. The park covers around 2,000 hectares and the headline scenery is the Sumacbao River cutting between vertical limestone walls. The water is clear and jade-green, the bamboo raft ride is the standard way to see the canyon up close, and the day trip from Manila is doable if you leave early.</p>
<p>This is the practical first-timer plan for Minalungao, with the bus route, the raft and zipline options, and what to bring when the river gets full of weekend crowds.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX north to the Cabanatuan exit, then continue on the Maharlika Highway to Cabanatuan City. From Cabanatuan, follow the road to General Tinio, then the signs to Minalungao National Park. Total drive time is around three to four hours without traffic.</p>
<h3>By Bus</h3>
<p>Take a Cabanatuan-bound bus from Cubao on <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> or Five Star, around three hours. From Cabanatuan, ride a jeepney or van to General Tinio, then a tricycle to the park entrance. The total transit is around five hours, so this is the slower but more affordable option.</p>
<h2>At the Park Entrance</h2>
<p>Pay the small environmental fee at the gate. The fee covers the day-use of the park grounds and is separate from the raft, zipline, and cave activities, which are paid per activity at the riverside booths.</p>
<h3>What the River Looks Like</h3>
<p>The Sumacbao River runs through the center of the park, walled in on both sides by 16-meter limestone cliffs in places. The water is clear enough to see the river bed for most of the year, and the color shifts from deep emerald in the morning to a brighter jade in the noon light.</p>
<h2>The Bamboo Raft Ride</h2>
<p>The bamboo raft is the signature activity. The rafts are large enough for a small group, and a local boatman poles you along the river through the limestone canyon. The ride lasts around an hour, with stops for swimming and for photos at the narrower sections of the canyon.</p>
<h3>What to Expect</h3>
<ul>
<li>Slow movement through the canyon, no rapids</li>
<li>One or two stops for swimming in the deeper pools</li>
<li>Optional drop-off at the small waterfalls at the canyon end</li>
<li>Return to the main beach area for lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Other Activities in the Park</h2>
<h3>Zipline</h3>
<p>A zipline runs across the river canyon from one cliff to the other. The ride is short but the view of the river below is the payoff. Pay at the zipline booth and follow the staff up the ladder to the platform.</p>
<h3>Cave Spelunking</h3>
<p>A small cave system near the river entrance is open for guided exploration. The guide leads you through tight passages with limestone formations and a small underground stream. The cave is short and beginner-friendly, around 30 minutes total.</p>
<h3>Cliff Jumping</h3>
<p>Some sections of the canyon have low cliff-jump platforms. Only jump where the boatman or guide confirms the depth, the river bed has rocky sections in places.</p>
<h2>Lunch Options</h2>
<p>The picnic huts at the riverside are first-come first-served. Bring your own packed lunch or rent a hut and order from the small carinderias near the entrance. The food is standard Filipino fare: grilled chicken, sinigang, fried fish, and rice. There are no big restaurants on site.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Swim clothes and a quick-dry towel</li>
<li>Aqua shoes or sandals with grip for the rocky river bed</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the noon sun on the river is intense</li>
<li>A hat or cap and sunglasses</li>
<li>Cash for the entrance fee, the activities, and the food, no card payments</li>
<li>Trash bags, the park is leave-no-trace and the rangers check</li>
<li>Insect repellent for the afternoon</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the best window. The water is clearer and the river is calm. The wet season swells the river and turns the water brown, and some activities get suspended. Weekends fill up fast with day-trippers from Cabanatuan and Manila, so weekday visits are noticeably calmer.</p>
<h2>Pairing the Day</h2>
<p>If you have a full weekend, pair Minalungao with a stop at the Pantabangan Dam on the other side of Nueva Ecija, or with the farm-stay nights at one of the Cabiao agri-tourism farms. The province is more than a Sierra Madre crossing point to Aurora, and the farm scene is steadily growing.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>Most day-trippers head back to Manila in the late afternoon. If you want to stay overnight, the nearest hotel inventory is in Cabanatuan City. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g6298440-Cabanatuan_Nueva_Ecija_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Minalungao is the quiet Nueva Ecija day trip that earns the long drive. Plan the early start, ride the bamboo raft, and let the canyon do the work.</p>
