<p>Donsol in Sorsogon has been running an ethical whale shark interaction program since 1998, with strict community-managed rules that have shaped the way visitors meet butanding, the local name for the species. The program is no-touch, no-feed, and snorkel-only, which is the longest-standing version of this practice in the country. This is the practical read on the season, the boat rules, and what to expect from the day.</p>
<h2>The Season</h2>
<p>The whale shark season in Donsol runs from November to June, with the peak between February and May. December and January are the lowest predictability months, with sightings still possible but less reliable. If your trip is built around the interaction, plan for the March to May window.</p>
<h3>The Off Season</h3>
<p>Outside the season, the whale sharks have moved to other feeding grounds. The town and the bay are still beautiful for a slow stay, but the boats do not run the interaction tours and the BIO orientation room is closed.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>The most reliable way is to fly into Legazpi, Albay, on <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or Philippine Airlines. From Legazpi airport, take a van direct to Donsol, around two hours through the Sorsogon countryside. Most resorts arrange the airport transfer if you ask.</p>
<h3>By Bus</h3>
<p>From Manila, the long-haul bus to Sorsogon City takes around 12 hours overnight. From Sorsogon City, the jeepney or van to Donsol takes around 45 minutes. This is the cheapest route but most travelers prefer the flight option for the time savings.</p>
<h2>At the BIO Visitor Center</h2>
<p>The day starts at the Butanding Interaction Officer (BIO) visitor center in Donsol. The required orientation video runs around 15 minutes and covers the interaction rules, the species biology, and the conservation history. After the orientation, you register, pay the interaction fee, and get assigned to a boat with a licensed BIO and a spotter.</p>
<h3>The Rules</h3>
<ul>
<li>No touching, no riding, no chasing</li>
<li>Stay at least 3 meters from the head and 4 meters from the tail</li>
<li>Snorkel only, no scuba</li>
<li>No flash photography</li>
<li>Maximum 6 swimmers per shark at a time</li>
<li>Follow the BIO's instructions on when to enter the water</li>
</ul>
<p>The rules are strictly enforced. Violations result in immediate return to shore and a possible ban from future interactions.</p>
<h2>The Boat Day</h2>
<p>The boats leave the Donsol pier around 7:30 a.m. and spend the morning cruising the coastal waters where the whale sharks are most likely. The spotter on the bow watches for the dark shapes near the surface. When a butanding is spotted, the BIO directs the group to enter the water quietly, in pairs or threes, with fins and snorkels.</p>
<h3>The Interaction</h3>
<p>The actual swim with a butanding lasts only a few minutes per encounter. The shark is moving steadily, and the boat circles to give the group a second or third attempt at the same animal. On a good day, the boat finds three to five sharks across the morning. On a slow day, you may only see one, or none.</p>
<h3>The Return</h3>
<p>The boats return to the pier by noon. Lunch is at the resort or at one of the carinderias near the visitor center. The afternoon is yours for the slow stay in town.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Your own snorkel and mask if you have them, the rentals are fine but a personal fit is better</li>
<li>Long-sleeve rashguard, the sun on the open boat is brutal</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the bay marine life is the point</li>
<li>A hat or cap and sunglasses for the boat ride</li>
<li>A dry bag for your phone and camera</li>
<li>Motion sickness meds if you are sensitive, the open sea can swell</li>
<li>A waterproof camera or housing if you want underwater photos</li>
<li>Cash for the BIO fee, the boat fee, and the resort meals</li>
</ul>
<h2>Other Activities in Donsol</h2>
<h3>Firefly Cruise</h3>
<p>The Ogod River firefly cruise runs in the evening, around 6:30 p.m. The boat takes you upriver through the mangroves where the fireflies cluster on the trees in the dark. The display is best on moonless nights and during the dry season. The cruise lasts around an hour and is the calm activity that pairs naturally with the morning whale shark day.</p>
<h3>Sandbar Mainit</h3>
<p>The Mainit Sandbar appears at low tide off the Donsol coast and disappears at high tide. The bar is good for a calm afternoon visit, with a banca ride from the pier and a quick swim or walk on the sand.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>Donsol has a small but workable inventory of resorts and inns along the beach and in the town center. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g1227037-Donsol_Sorsogon_Province_Bicol_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Book ahead during the peak season.</p>
<h2>The Honest Read</h2>
<p>Whale shark interactions are weather-dependent and animal-dependent. Plan two days minimum in Donsol to give yourself a second boat day if the first one comes up empty. The BIO operators are honest about the day's prospects in the morning briefing, so listen carefully and adjust expectations. The town's program is one of the few in the country that puts the animals first, and that is worth supporting even on the slow days.</p>
<p>Donsol earns the trip because the program is run right. Plan around the season, follow the BIO rules, and the bay does the rest.</p>
